a poll on wednesday put gov michael dukakis in 
a dead heat with vice president george bush in the presidential 
contest and a second survey also indicated dukakis was losing 
ground to his republican rival but still clinging to a lead 
a telephone survey of 1013 adults last week by abc news and 
money magazine found 45 percent support for dukakis and 42 percent 
for bush a tie given the margin of error of plus or minus 4 
percentage points 
and a gallup poll of 1210 voters suggested dukakis had the 
support of 46 percent to 41 percent for bush the margin of error 
was 3 percentage points 
by contrast gallup nbc newswall street journal and washington 
post polls conducted since june 9 have found doubledigit leads for 
dukakis the post survey done june 1519 found a 5139 percent 
dukakis margin 
the abcmoney magazine poll conducted june 2225 found support 
for dukakis down 7 points from an abcpost poll in midmay that 
used the same methodology bush rose only from 41 to 42 percent 
support those who didnt know grew from 2 percent to 6 percent 
the rest said they wouldnt vote or would support someone else 
poll analysts have said they expected the race to tighten as 
dukakis came off the crest of his democratic primary victories a 
harris survey early this month found a dead heat 4944 with a 
3point margin of error and a usa todaycnn poll gave dukakis a 
singledigit lead 
the abcmoney magazine poll had dukakis leading among women 
respondents earning less than 25000 a year and adults aged 35 to 
54 bush led among men respondents earning more than 50000 and 
those in the 5564 age group 
