<TEXT>
from christmas trees to canned peas trouble is brewing 
from cherries in the trees to honey from the bees from tomatoes 
to potatoes the suffocating drought in midamerica is taking its 
toll on scores of smaller crops that could result in huge losses 
for thousands of growers 
it will affect just about everything grown from the rocky 
mountains east to ohio just about anything you consume that 
comes from these parts of the country said neil harl economics 
professor at iowa state university 
while much of the spotlight about the droughts impact has 
focused on the enormous grain and livestock industries the worst 
dry spell since the dust bowl also threatens such foods as fruits 
and oysters 
when everyone talks about programs the usda and the 
government its always corn soybeans wheat cotton and 
peanuts said harry foster secretarymanager of the red tart 
cherry growers in michigan everybody else in the world that 
grows the 200 other things theyre sort of forgotten 
michigan cherries used for baking juices and jams are 
suffering he said and the trees are beginning to show stress 
foster said about 150 million pounds of tart cherries will be 
harvested in the state in the next six weeks about 100 million 
pounds less than normal 
all across the midwest and southeast other crops hit by the 
drought could shrink supplies change diets and raise prices at 
grocery stores restaurants and taverns 
the drought has pushed barley prices higher raising the 
possibility of higher beer costs one analyst said if the price of 
barley goes through the roof the retail price of beer could 
increase by up to 4 percent 
in alabama some farmers are worried they could lose half their 
potato crop much of which is used for chips in louisiana the low 
level of the mississippi river has allowed saltwater to move 
upstream making oysters more susceptible to predators and 
imperiling next years crop said mark chatry marine laboratory 
director at louisianas department of wildlife and fisheries 
a dike is being built to block the saltwater flow 
in north georgia some honey production has dried up in 
wisconsin the pea crop has shrunk and across the midwest 
thousands of christmas trees planted this spring which wont 
mature for several years have been lost 
gene gress who runs a christmas tree farm with his wife in 
polar wis said he lost the 10000 trees he planted this spring 
because of the maturation period though consumers wont likely 
notice until the mid1990s 
other midwest growers already have talked of losses of 30 
percent of this years planting that could rise to 60 percent 
without rain in two weeks said david bauman associate executive 
director of the national christmas tree association 
the arid sunny days also will cut the number and size of 
apples tomatoes cucumbers cabbage beans and peas 
farmer richard sorenson of oregon wis said because of a 
record 40 straight days without moisture he doesnt expect profits 
from 20 acres of peas he planted 
i got 1250 pounds to the acre about a fourth of normal he 
said when i figured out the costs for seed fertilizing and 
hauling i owe 312 
and that ultimately affects canned goods producers 
stokely usa inc could be looking at a 25 percent to 30 percent 
shortfall of its normal year of 25 million cases of corn bean 
peas and mixed vegetables said stephen theobald vice 
presidentadminstration 
everything from green beans to tomatoes its all going to be 
in short supply he said the quality wont be as good the 
prices will be higher 
its one of those situations where everybodys the loser 
from the grower to the processor to the consumer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sharon cohen is the ap midwest regional 
reporter based in chicago 
</TEXT>
