<TEXT>
when she looks out her window lynn 
johansen sees a little boy who reminds her of the teenage brother 
she lost during a navy water training exercise 
the boy is mrs johansens 6yearold son bradley a lookalike 
for his uncle lee mirecki the 19yearold recruit who died in 
march at the navy rescue swimmer school in pensacola fla 
now nearly four months later four instructors are facing 
nonjudicial hearings in the case but mireckis family and a close 
friend said monday they still wonder why the bright young recruit 
died 
i dont think anybody really knows what happened said mrs 
johansen 30 she said she came away from the military hearing 
earlier this month a little more bewildered in trying to separate 
true fact from speculation 
mirecki was described at the investigative hearing as being 
literally scared to death when he was allegedly forced into the 
pool after he tried to quit testimony indicated he was held under 
water after he had escaped once from the pool and clung to the side 
but was dragged back during an exercise known as sharks and 
daisies it was intended to train swimmers how to break the 
strangle hold of someone they were trying to rescue 
the four instructors accepted the navy prosecutors offer for 
the nonjudicial hearings on whether they should be punished with 
pay or rank cuts or other nonjudicial action a courtmartial has 
been recommended for a fifth instructor 
the officer who was in charge of the school rejected an offer 
for a nonjudicial hearing his case will be reevaluated to decide 
whether to drop a charge of dereliction of duty or recommend 
courtmartial 
i did find a lot of things out but i guess the question that 
will always be in my mind is why didnt they let him dor or drop 
on request from the program said mireckis mother elaine kitowski 
of manitowish waters it was through the persistence of the family 
that an investigation into the recruits death was finally launched 
mrs kitowski said she misses most the jokes and humor of her 
youngest of four children lee often taped her scissors together or 
hid her keys 
he was a gogetter a very active boy said mrs kitowski 
an active soccer and baseball player mirecki moved to appleton 
to live with mrs johansen and her family for two years to be 
closer to a high school with more sports activities 
mrs johansen who has collected boxes of information about her 
brothers death said the family never sought to blame any 
individual but she said they wanted to know what had happened 
if he did die what looks to be a horrible terrifying death 
that could have been prevented ill hopefully find out enough to 
prevent it from ever happening again she said 
those who knew him described mirecki as a determined young man 
who was used to winning and was no quitter 
he hated to lose but he didnt lose very often said laurie 
radewan 28 of racine mireckis other sister whether you were 
outside playing football or in the house playing monopoly hed 
cream you 
he told his close friend james woller that he wanted to become a 
psychologist someday but he joined the navy after graduating from 
appleton high schoolwest because he also wanted to fly and thought 
the military could help him get the money he needed to attend 
college 
he grew up near the water boating swimming and fishing 
lee was not afraid of the water said larry johansen 
mireckis brotherinlaw 
but lee hated being dunked or dragged under water a fear 
stemming from a dunking incident by older boys when he was 5 his 
father rescued the crying coughing youngster mrs johansen said 
he never mentioned it but we all knew you dont dunk lee 
because he would get real angry she said 
years later he told his family he was having difficulty with 
the navy rescue swimmer school 
mrs radewan said she never realized the extent of her brothers 
fear and does not think he did either 
he grew up on a lake he enjoyed the water but he didnt like 
people jumping on him she said he just didnt like to feel 
