<DOCNO> AP880629-0015 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
unable to turn back the advancing sahara 
desert or stop periodic droughts niger has turned to family 
planning to control population growth and reduce pressure on its 
fragile resources 
the northcentral african nation has only 68 million people in 
an area twice the size of france but it cant feed itself and at 
its current growth rate the population will double in 23 years 
three and a half years ago the government strongly endorsed 
family planning an unprecedented move in this largely moslem area 
of africa just below the sahara and in april it legalized 
contraception 
the legalization of contraception is concrete proof of the 
governments support for family planning said dr halima 
maidouka diallo director of family planning in the ministry of 
health 
to counter african traditions in favor of large families and 
avoid potential clashes with some interpretations of the koran the 
moslems holy book the government presented family planning as a 
necessary move to reduce infant and maternal mortality 
nigers infant mortality rate of 135 deaths per 1000 births and 
maternal mortality rate of 7 deaths per 1000 births are among the 
highest in the world 
for a woman to be valued here she must have many children as 
soon as possible children help with work and are considered life 
insurance maidouka said 
women are considered wicked if they do not produce children 
she added 
customarily if a woman doesnt bear children a husband will 
look for another wife 
because many infants die mothers bear many children it is not 
unusual for a mother to have 15 children with only five surviving 
the frequent births become both a cause and effect women become 
pregnant again as soon as possible after delivery without time to 
fully recover and often give birth prematurely to infants who have 
little chance of surviving 
it also creates problems in schools where many young girls 
become pregnant the average age for marriage for women is about 
15 
some women seek abortions clandestinely as they are not legal 
here or go to neighboring countries 
at least once a month there is a case of a baby being 
strangled and tossed in a trash can maidouka said 
she added that suicides are also a problem among women with 
unwanted pregnancies 
the family planning program seeks to offer women an alternative 
a child if i want when i want says a poster displayed 
throughout the countrys main family planning center 
the center built with funding from the united nations has a 
large poster explaining various contraception methods the 
explanations are accompanied by explicit diagrams showing among 
other things how to use a condom 
the diagrams are necessary in a nation where only 44 percent of 
the women are literate and only 20 percent of children go to 
primary schools 
dr voahangi ravao of malagasy a staff associate of the 
columbia university center for population and family health says 
the most common reason given in a niamey survey of women who did 
not use family planning was nobody told me 
opposition by husbands was cited by only 5 percent she said 
she added that she has seen women whove walked 10 miles to pick 
up birth control pills 
she said a survey taken a year ago showed 6 to 10 percent of the 
women were using some form of modern contraception which is a very 
high rate for the sahel the region just below the sahara 
in the west african nation of burkina faso for example a 
similar survey found 4 to 6 percent of women using modern birth 
control methods 
maidouka said radio and television broadcasts in the main 
national languages will be used to reach as many people as 
possible 
the us agency for international development has approved an 
11million fiveyear grant to support the project 
in a report the agency said nigers rapid population growth 
has accentuated the processes of deforestation and 
desertification 
it added wood harvesting which provides 80 percent of the 
nations energy far exceeds the sustainable capacity of the 
forests the forested area has decreased by 30 percent over the 
last 20 years due to pressure from farmers herders firewood 
cutters and drought 
only 12 percent of the country is arable and only 3 percent can 
be used for growing crops the annual per capita income is 240 
the us agencys report concedes that even if couples were 
limited immediately to two children per family the population would 
continue to grow for 40 years because almost half the current 
population are teenagers and the agency says it is likely to take 
30 years to reach the goal of only two children per family 
the familyplanning project however doesnt even talk of 
limiting families to two children 
it focuses on how planning and spacing of pregnancies will mean 
better health for mother and child 
there is much to do maidouka said tradition is a 
problem perhaps our children will have full rights now the man is 
the boss 
</TEXT>
