<TEXT>
attorney general edwin meese iii spoke at 
length at a news conference about the pentagon bribery 
investigation but never mentioned that he had removed himself from 
decisions in the case a day earlier because his own lawyers 
represent clients in the probe 
the burgeoning defense department contract fraud investigation 
was the dominant topic at meeses news conference tuesday 
afternoon generating nine questions meese told reporters that 
earlier tuesday he had briefed defense secretary frank carlucci 
who is trying to determine whether to take administrative action 
against any contractors or pentagon employees 
at the same news conference meese volunteered that he was 
recused from a justice department civil suit against the teamsters 
union because they were the main union that endorsed president 
reagan in 1980 and meese was a top campaign official 
but he said not a word about stepping aside in the pentagon 
probe 
in response to questions tuesday night from the associated 
press justice department spokesman patrick korten said meeses 
recusal was relayed to top top justice officials in a memo sent 
monday by edward dennis acting assistant attorney general in 
charge of the criminal division 
korten said meese did not mention his recusal at the news 
conference because there wasnt any particular reason to mention 
it 
korten said the attorney generals law firm miller cassidy 
larroca amp lewin keeps him informed of what clients they have 
that may have business pending before the department and in those 
cases meese recuses himself to be safe 
miller cassidy has two clients with some connection with the 
defense investigation korten said he said he did not know who 
the clients were 
the law firm represents meese in the yearold investigation by 
independent counsel james mckay into whether meese used public 
office to favor friends or companies which may have in turn 
rewarded him or his family 
meese has denied any wrongdoing mckay whose report should be 
released in two weeks is not expected to seek any indictment of 
meese though mckay is expected to refer several matters to justice 
ethics officials to see if administrative discipline is warranted 
james rocap one of meeses attorneys declined to say whether 
the firm had any clients in the defense case but did say it had a 
routine arrangement to get meese recused quickly from any cases 
involving its other clients 
although some democrats in congress have said meeses legal 
troubles including his extensive recusals hamper his ability to 
run the justice department korten said as a practical matter 
he very rarely gets involved in the specific details of any case 
so it has little practical effect 
in many law firms and in the justice department in the past 
recusal from a case barred the affected lawyer not only from making 
decisions but also from receiving briefings for fear he might 
subtly influence decisions 
asked if meese would continue to get pentagon case briefings 
korten said ill have to check with him on that recusal just 
means he doesnt make decisions 
korten said meese answered the new conference questions on the 
basis of what chief prosecutor henry hudson and ed dennis have 
indicated about the way they intend to proceed in briefings he had 
before he was recused 
at the news conference meese was asked when more information 
would be made public he replied from this stage on i expect a 
lot less information coming out rather than more until such time as 
the grand jury investigation is complete 
he added it may take longer than the 30 to 90 days he had 
earlier predicted for the first indictments to be returned 
asked if former reagan administration defense secretary caspar 
weinberger had been lax in policing contract fraud meese replied 
certainly nothing that i know about nor have i seen anything in 
what i know about the case so far that would indicate that there 
was any laxity or lapse on the part of mr weinberger 
meese has been criticized privately by some justice officials 
for applying recusals narrowly they object to his continued 
participation in the case of convicted israeli spy jonathan pollard 
while miller cassidy represents col avi sella an israeli officer 
who is charged with recruiting pollard to spy but who has never 
returned to this country for trial 
justice spokesmen say meese participates in aspects of the 
pollard case that do not involve sella 
