<TEXT>
every sweltering 
day folks carrying buckets thermoses and jugs turn on the outside 
tap at the ez stop convenience store and fill up 
to leone johnson providing drinking water to her customers and 
neighbors is no big deal to many living on the fort berthold 
reservation indian and nonindian it is a gesture of friendship 
deeply appreciated 
mrs johnsons store gets city water thats been filtered and 
chlorinated many of the nearby wells the only reliable source of 
water for thousands in northwestern north dakota yield brown water 
full of salt and foultasting minerals 
chemically the well water tests safe to drink but it tastes 
almost as bad as it looks said rich schilf natural resources 
director of the three affiliated tribes 
holding up a jug containing water the color of crude oil schilf 
said one of my coworkers brought this in from his house this 
morning and dared me to drink it i decided to pass 
most of the groundwater on the reservation is terrible full 
of sodium added schilf whos tried for years to get a 
longpromised federally funded water system installed on the 
reservation almost everybody hauls their drinking water if 
theyre not hooked up to the new town system 
new town the reservations population center with 1300 
residents has doubled its pumping since drought settled on this 
high parched prairie two months ago 
were pumping 600000 gallons a day to try and meet the 
demand said bill folven at the treatment plant despite new 
towns being within sight of a huge missouri river reservoir the 
town gets its drinking water from three deep wells 
the water plant sells the precious commodity by the 
quarterdollar 
you get 100 gallons for each quarter said folven who 
empties the coin box and says these days its usually full 
many people on the reservation carry big tanks on their pickup 
trucks they drive to the plant park under a pipe jutting from the 
concrete block building put quarters in the meter press a button 
and stand back as the water runs 
elmer rambel has run a commercial water delivery service around 
new town for years 
usually elmer gets his water from a spring but his filtration 
system broke so hes buying it from the city and hauling it to 
us said myrna jacobs a mother of five who deals in real estate 
with the three affiliated tribes 
usually i pay 25 for 2200 gallons to be delivered to our 
cistern but two weeks ago elmer had to raise his price to 31 
she said despite trying to be real careful and conserve water i 
had to have two truckloads of water delivered to the house last 
month and im sure it will be the same for june 
mrs johnson says she gives her water away in small quantities 
because ive lived here all my life and the people who need my 
water to drink are neighbors and friends and customers whose 
business i appreciate 
she says it doesnt matter how much higher her water bill will 
run 
its something i can do that helps she said 
</TEXT>
