<TEXT>
us relations with mexico are never 
harmonious even in the best of times and a recent episode involving 
mexicos handling of a puerto rican separatist wanted by the united 
states is bound to deepen mutual distrust 
mexico ignored a us request for the extradition of william 
morales 37 and instead granted him early release last friday from 
an eightyear prison term he was then deported to cuba 
mexico views morales as a man who was persecuted in the united 
states for his political views the united states sees him as a 
terrorist and says he was involved in more than 50 bombings in the 
us that resulted in widespread death and injury 
morales had been sentenced to more than 100 years in prison but 
escaped from us custody in 1979 he fled to mexico where four 
years later he was convicted in the killing of a police officer 
despite strong us interest in the case mexico did not 
formally notify american officials of morales release and 
deportation until five days after his arrival in havana safely 
beyond the reach of us authorities 
the us ambassador to mexico charles pilliod has been 
recalled to washington for consultations but it seems unlikely the 
administration will take significant retaliatory action against 
mexico 
the main argument against economic sanctions is that they harm 
the united states as much as mexico by increasing the flow of 
undocumented aliens the administrations options appear to be 
limited 
a key role in the morales case apparently was played by foreign 
secretary bernardo sepulveda it was he who formally rejected the 
us extradition request overriding a ruling last december by a 
mexico city judge 
sepulveda ranks as perhaps the state departments most disliked 
foreign minister one official said sepulveda and assistant 
secretary of state elliott abrams have a shoot on sight 
relationship 
sepulveda is not a favorite of secretary of state george p 
shultz either at one point several years ago shultzs aides 
considered contriving an excuse for shultz to back out of a 
scheduled meeting with sepulveda to spare him what promised to be 
an unpleasant encounter but shultz went ahead with the meeting 
anyway 
much of the usmexican hostility is based on mexicos support 
for nicaraguas leftist government and to a lesser extent the 
rebel movement in el salvador mexico and cuba and more recently 
panama are nicaraguas strongest supporters in the hemisphere 
sepulveda is described here as an advocate of selling oil to 
nicaragua at concessional rates even though nicaragua has a 
reputation as a poor credit risk 
this has put sepulveda at odds with mexican ministries 
responsible for economic matters american officials say that on 
two occasions vessels carrying mexican oil to nicaragua were 
called home before reaching their destination on both occasions 
sepulveda was overruled by president miguel de la madrids 
financial advisers 
sepulveda has maintained that the united states made a big 
mistake by supporting an armed insurrection against the sandinista 
government he has said cooperation with nicaragua would make it 
more likely to pursue moderate policies he views with disdain 
president reagans assertion that failure to oppose the sandinistas 
eventually could raise the prospect of a leftist uprising in mexico 
itself 
despite the lack of trust the administration was caught by 
surprise when mexico released morales and allowed him to go to 
cuba white house spokesman marlin fitzwater called the decision an 
inexplicable affront 
state department spokesman charles redman said morales violent 
criminal past was so selfevident that his release and deportation 
could only have been taken for political reasons 
the two countries can only hope that a change in administration 
in both will lead to a more harmonious relationship mexico will 
elect a new president next month and the united states will do the 
same in november new teams and perhaps new approaches will be 
in place by early next year 
</TEXT>
