<TEXT>
the senate sponsor of a 25 billion child 
care expansion bill says hes willing to compromise on some parts 
of the measure but wont give up on minimum national standards for 
day care providers 
sen christopher dodd dconn told two governors urging 
continued state regulation of day care that they would be shocked 
to find the tremendous disparity in standards from state to state 
dodd later said he would not abandon the minimum health safety 
training staff ratio and other standards called for in his act for 
better child care or abc bill in favor of standards meant to 
serve as models for the states 
you are deluding yourself if you believe model standards get 
used he told reporters theyve got to be more than that 
dodd chairman of the senate labor and human resources 
subcommittee on children family drugs and alcoholism held a 
hearing a luncheon two panel discussions and a reception tuesday 
to discuss the abc bill 
threefourths of the abc money would help pay day care expenses 
for families making less than 115 percent of a states median 
income the remaining money would be for training and salaries of 
child care workers renovation of facilities and referral programs 
for parents 
money would only be available to day care homes and centers that 
met minimum federal standards developed by an advisory panel the 
bill is supported by scores of groups representing women children 
labor and medical personnel 
the leadoff hearing witnesses govs bill clinton of arkansas 
and thomas kean of new jersey representing the national governors 
association said they are anxious for a day care initiative this 
year even if it is less generous than the plan envisioned by dodd 
dont pass nothing just because you cant get as much money as 
you want clinton a democrat told sen tom harkin diowa 
after harkin said child care boosters would never be able to get 
25 billion 
whatever way you can help us we need that help added kean 
a republican whatever money you give us will be put to 
extraordinarily good use 
clinton and kean asked dodd to reconsider several aspects of the 
abc bill most of them the same provisions that have sparked 
criticism from conservative lawmakers and lobbyists 
the governors concerns included the mandatory national provider 
standards as well as eligibility standards for day care aid with 
the cutoff at 115 percent of median state income some families 
making 40000 would qualify 
clinton and kean also said the private sector should be given 
incentives to play a bigger role in day care and states should be 
able to use federal money flexibly perhaps through a broad child 
care block grant 
dodd said he would continue working with the governors on his 
bill he told reporters that it could be argued that weve gone a 
little too high on the income eligibility standards but said he 
wants lower middle income taxpayers to support the program 
were trying to reach up to those people who dont fall 
into the poverty category but still need some assistance dodd 
said theres a substantive need as well as a political 
justification for giving these people some help but its not a 
yuppie bill the bulk of this assistance goes to people who are in 
desperate need of help 
over 100 child care bills are pending in congress introduced by 
lawmakers from all across the political spectrum some offer tax 
incentives to businesses to start child care centers while others 
offer tax credits to all families with preschool children one bill 
would increase the existing social services block grant and 
another would limit provider liability through insurance risk 
pools other proposals involve vouchers for poor families and aid 
to providers for capital improvements 
