parliament has banned tobacco advertising and 
forbidden smoking in federally regulated workplaces and 
transportation 
the senate on tuesday passed two bills that the tobacco industry 
had fought for more than a year the bills approved may 30 by the 
house of commons were signed tuesday by governor general jeanne 
sauve 
one bill calls for smokefree workplaces in companies regulated 
by the federal government that includes banks telecommunications 
firms and crown corporations 
the measure also guarantees smokefree traveling on planes 
ships trains and buses that offer passenger service and are 
federally regulated 
the second bill bans tobacco ads on television radio 
newspapers billboards and magazines 
the tobacco industry said the prohibition on ads amounted to an 
infringement on the right of freedom of speech the ad ban takes 
effect next jan 1 but some signs will be permitted until 1993 
imported broadcasts and publications may still carry tobacco 
ads about twothirds of the periodicals distributed in canada come 
from the united states 
another section of the bill outlaws free samples of tobacco all 
tobacco products will have to carry a health warning approved by 
the federal government 
companies violating the strict provisions may be fined up to 
300000 
tobacco is a 48 billion industry in canada and employs 60000 
people one quarter of the canadian population smokes the habit is 
blamed for contributing to 35000 deaths a year in canada 
governments at every level have tightened restrictions on 
smoking the federal government has banned smoking on commercial 
airline flights of two hours or less and many cities already 
outlaw smoking in the workplace except for designated rooms 
 
