<TEXT>
a shortage of staff attorneys is causing the 
federal aviation administration to have more and more difficulties 
following up on the growing number of safety violations its 
inspectors uncover government officials say 
inspector general john w melchner of the department of 
transportation told a house subcommittee tuesday that it often 
takes the faa an inordinate amount of time to process cases 
against people or companies found to have violated safety 
regulations about 45 percent of the cases have been open for more 
than a year he said 
melchner told members of the house public works committees 
investigations and oversight subcommittee that the number of 
violations discovered by faa inspectors has more than doubled from 
28864 in 1984 to 63391 in 1987 
despite that growth the faa added only 17 additional lawyers to 
handle the growing volume of cases he said 
faa administrator allan mcartor agreed complaining that 
although the faa has been building up its force of safety 
inspectors the number of attorneys who handle the problems that 
are discovered has not kept pace 
it will do us little good to continue to increase our 
inspector levels if we cannot attain the necessary complement of 
lawyers to take enforcement actions against safety violators 
uncovered by our inspectors mcartor said 
melchner said the number of faa inspectors has grown from 1320 
in 1984 to 1930 last year and there are plans to hire 1028 more 
by 1991 inspectors examine the operations of airlines and 
privately owned aircraft airports and service companies 
faa spokesman fred farrar said there are 129 faa lawyers 
sixtyeight of them work in field offices across the country and 
handle most of the violations uncovered he said 
mcartor said his agency has probably its highest backlog 
ever of cases its lawyers are trying to pursue he said he did 
not have statistics about the backedup cases 
at the same hearing melchner faulted the faa for inadequately 
investigating complaints from three ryan air service pilots that 
the alaskan airline pressured them to make overloaded flights 
one of the three pilots who unsuccessfully had sought immunity 
from the faa in exchange for testimony about falsified flight 
records was later among 18 people killed in an accident that was 
blamed on an excessively heavy load of passengers and cargo 
as a result of the ryan air crash the faa official who decided 
against granting immunity to the pilots was reassigned the faa 
changed some of its investigative procedures and the government 
halted ryan airs flights 
melchner told the subcommittee that his investigation of the 
faas response to the pilots complaints did not find a 
wellcoordinated aggressive safety enforcement program in place in 
the alaska region 
melchner also said he could not explain why the faas counsel 
who was responsible for alaska donald boberick decided not to 
grant immunity to the pilots 
according to melchner a ryan air mechanic approached faa 
officials in september 1986 on behalf of the three pilots asking 
for immunity for the pilots in exchange for testimony about false 
information they said was being supplied about flight loads 
one of the pilots was killed when a ryan flight crashed at 
homer alaska last nov 23 that flight was later found to have 
been overweight by 460 pounds 
last january the anchorage daily news reported that the three 
pilots had made their offer to the faa the article sparked 
melchners investigation the results of which were sent to mcartor 
in march 
