<TEXT>
pale and tired anwara begum was 
frying grains of wheat while her two small sons hovered around her 
makeshift little stove in a relief center for hundreds of flood 
victims set up at a school 
mummy we are hungry give us food one of the naked little 
boys cried 
their father 45year sanu miah stood by helplessly tears 
welling in his eyes and running down his wrinkled cheeks 
we have had very little to eat since floods destroyed my 
house he told a visiting reporter tuesday the children are in 
especially terrible condition 
his wife anwara had fashioned a primitive stove from an empty 
powdered milk can her children about 6 and 8 were so hungry she 
had not taken time to grind her grains of wheat into flour 
miah clad in a torn sarong was among 500 people who sought 
shelter at the at the syed saiduddin high school after 
monsoonswollen rivers surged through villages and fields around 
noapara little more than a railway stop on the train line from 
dhaka the capital to sylhet 200 miles to the northeast 
an estimated 13 million people more than 10 percent of 
bangladeshs population of 105 million have been stranded or 
displaced by floods 
in the past week at least 39 people have died in this country 
shredded by hundreds of rivers that surge over their banks every 
year when the monsoon rains come about half the deaths were in the 
sylhet area 
in noapara about 95 miles northeast of dhaka the syed 
saiduddin school has suspended classes to offer shelter to people 
whose homes were washed away or damaged by the floods 
a few blocks from the school are the remains of the railroad 
bridge that was swept away on sunday making noapara the last stop 
for travelers from dhaka trying to reach nearby sylhet the 
commercial center of dhakas teagrowing district 
roads throughout sylhet and the surrounding districts of 
sunamganj and moulvibazar in the far northeastern corner of 
bangladesh were also washed out or still under water 
miah who owns no land and hires himself out as an unskilled 
laborer from day to day does not know what he will do next he has 
not decided whether to try to rebuild his house in rasulpur 
village seven miles east of noapara or to seek a new life 
elsewhere 
he said the flash floods arrived with a loud bang and swirled 
waisthigh through his mud and straw house 
but his neighbor 55yearold muzaffar ali has decided to 
return home and try again noapara is a hilly area where flash 
floods cascade through the villages and fields and quickly recede 
as the water surges downstream 
the refugees said thousands of mud and straw houses had 
disappeared in the flood 
i am leaving the camp since water is no more there in 
rasulpur ali said surrounded by his frail 40yearold wife 
and their three sons and two daughters 
what shall i eat and what shall i gather for my children he 
asked a vacant look on his face i have no land to till even 
still the people around noapara appear to have been luckier 
than countrymen in lowlying areas rivers continue to rise in 
flatter areas in the interior of the sylhet and sunamganj districts 
news reports in dhaka say at least 800000 people have been 
stranded by flooding in the sunamganj district alone 
the floods coupled with communication and transportation links 
that are erratic even in dry weather in bangladesh hamper relief 
efforts 
in noapara some private citizens and organizations have tried 
to provide relief according to mohammad ali a shopkeeper at the 
train station no local government officials could be located for 
comment on the situation when a reporter from dhaka visited noapara 
in dhaka officials said earlier in the week that tens of 
thousands of people perhaps more have taken refuge in government 
relief centers 
but the task is daunting bangladesh with a per capita income 
of about 150 a year is one of the worlds poorest nations last 
year more than 1200 people died in floods 
in 1985 more than 10000 people died in hurricanes and tidal 
waves that swept over low islands in the bay of bengal on the 
countrys south coast 
