the government announced today the 
release of 46 political prisoners including prominent dissident 
kim kuntae and said it would review the cases of other jailed 
radicals 
the justice ministry in a brief statement said the 46 would be 
released thursday from various prisons on parole ministry 
officials said 453 common criminals would also be paroled 
opposition groups have been demanding the release of hundreds of 
jailed dissidents they contend were imprisoned for political 
beliefs or antigovernment activity 
top opposition leader kim daejung told the national assembly 
today that more than 600 political prisoners remain in jail he 
called the continued detention of dissidents the main barrier to 
political peace in south korea 
how can we talk about reconciliation and political development 
while keeping in prison those patriots numbering more than 600 
who fought for democracy he said 
about 20 relatives of political prisoners demonstrated earlier 
today outside the headquarters of the governing democratic justice 
party to demand release of all prisoners they were taken away by 
police and released a short time later 
some opposition groups contend there are more than 1000 
political prisoners serving sentences or awaiting trial for 
antigovernment activity government officials say most of the 
prisoners committed violent crimes or violated national security 
laws 
the dissidents to be released thursday either demonstrated 
repentence or served a third of their sentences ministry officials 
said they said the cases of other dissidents will be reviewed on a 
monthly basis for possible releases 
kim kuntae appeared to be the only prominent figure among those 
to be released thursday 
sentenced in 1986 to five years in prison for inciting unrest 
he recently received the robert f kennedy award for human rights 
