<TEXT>
mikhail s gorbachevs plan to lease out state 
farmland could give soviet farmers the most control over their 
produce since josef v stalin forced the nations peasants to join 
collective farms nearly 60 years ago 
in a sweeping 3hour televised speech tuesday the soviet 
leader said it was essential to extend as quickly as possible 
successful experiments in leasing land to individuals or family 
farming teams 
the result he said would be to make the farmers the masters 
of the land 
this he suggested would be the quickest way to ease food 
shortages that he called the most painful and most acute problem 
in the life of our society 
gorbachev also proposed to spend 124 billion through 1995 to 
improve the processing storage and transportation of food 
if we manage to reap transport store and process the harvest 
promptly and to deliver to the consumer in good time we will 
increase food production by 20 to 30 percent without increasing 
the productivity of the land itself he said 
the son of a russian peasant gorbachev began his political 
career in an agricultural region and oversaw soviet agriculture 
from 1978 to late 1984 giving him many years of experience with 
the problems of tilling land in the huge state and collective farms 
created by stalin 
since taking over as soviet leader in march 1985 gorbachev has 
signaled his willingness to break down those big units as the only 
way to improve supplies in a nation where meat and milk are 
rationed in many regions 
addressing a national congress of collective farmers last march 
gorbachev called for broader freedoms in the farming industry 
on a collective farm members of a cooperative jointly own farm 
buildings and machinery and share in the farms earnings but those 
organizations have dwindled in recent decades in favor of state 
farms where workers farm the land in brigades and receive a basic 
wage like employees in a factory 
in 1970 there were 33000 kolkhozes or collective farms 
in the soviet union by 1986 the number of such farms had dropped 
to 26300 and the number of collective farmers from 167 million in 
1970 to 126 million 
gorbachev has tried to persuade soviets to return to cooperative 
farms encouraging the system to provide incentives to increase 
production and alleviate the chronic food shortage in the soviet 
union 
now he wants to expand a system that permits families to lease 
land from their collectives and farm it themselves 
to make the system work however the soviet union must revamp 
its state pricing structure to enable people to reap a fair return 
for their efforts gorbachev said tuesday 
one delegate to the conference pointed out the general 
secretarys proposal to expand the leasing system is hampered by a 
deeply ingrained conservatism in soviet society 
the problem is that our people have forgotten how to take 
risks said mikhail bronstein a leading economist from tartu 
university in the baltic republic of estonia 
he said that older people in estonia still remember the 
democracy that existed there until soviet troops seized the three 
baltic republics in 1940 
but even estonians are reluctant to take up these land 
leases bronstein said 
politburo member alexander n yakovlev said tuesday at a news 
conference that food shortages cannot be eased if the attitude of 
dependency on instructions and handouts continues to dominate 
state farming 
we must transform the countryside yakovlev said the 
countryside is in ruins 
he proposed giving state and collective farms more autonomy to 
decide themselves how and by what criteria they are ruled 
farmers long have complained they are not allowed to decide 
themselves how to till the land or rotate crops and are forced to 
follow rules set by local or even national party bureaucrats who 
know nothing about farming 
that system was set up by stalin who collectivized land in a 
brutal upheaval that caused a famine in which millions died in the 
early 1930s in the early 1920s during the formative years of the 
soviet state vladimir i lenin had made the peasantry relatively 
independent by allowing them to grow and sell their own produce 
elderly inhabitants of moscow recall to this day how lenins 
decision improved the food supply in the capital almost overnight 
