<TEXT>
federal officials ordered the mock 
evacuations of tens of thousands of people during a twoday 
exercise which pretended that a crippled seabrook nuclear power 
plant was spewing dangerous radiation 
nearly 3000 federal state local and utility officials and 
other workers participated tuesday on the first day of what 
seabrook officials say is the largest test ever of a us nuclear 
plants evacuation plans 
the plans must be approved before the 54 billion plant may 
operate commercially 
although the mock evacuations would have involved people on 
ocean beaches and in new hampshire and massachusetts communities up 
to five miles away most members of the public were unaware that 
the test was underway 
more than half the communities within seabrooks 10mile 
emergency planning zone six of 17 in new hampshire and all six in 
massachusetts are not cooperating in the drill 
as they did in a february 1986 exercise of the new hampshire 
plans state officials under proseabrook gov john sununu filled 
in for reluctant local officials among 55 deficiencies the federal 
emergency management agency found in the first exercise was 
insufficient compensation for noncooperating communities 
the test is the first for evacuation plans that seabrook 
developed for the massachusetts communities massachusetts gov 
michael dukakis the likely democratic presidential nominee 
refuses to submit plans that he said could never work 
its also the first test of procedures for monitoring food up to 
50 miles from seabrook an area that includes parts of maine 
only the tests controllers knew the scenario for the mock 
emergency they also have the power to improvise as they go along 
the exercise began with announcement of an imaginary accident 
and declaration of an ersatz alert the second lowest of four 
emergency classifications for nuclear plants 
seabrook officials opened emergency operations and media centers 
at a power station in newington while the state activated a field 
office there and emergency management headquarters in concord as 
the exercise progressed four reception centers in new hampshire 
and massachusetts also were opened but little other real activity 
was reported in the field 
the concord control center hummed however as representatives 
of various state agencies calmly talked on the phone and to each 
other took notes and marked off checklists about a dozen federal 
evaluators and exercise controllers watched 
officials took imaginary steps like closing some beaches they 
estimated 10000 people were on seabrook and hampton beaches on 
this theoretical cloudy summer day and ordering children kept in 
some schools as the scenario progressed to a site area 
emergency and a general emergency the most serious 
