nativeborn americans spend more time in 
hospitals or sick in bed at home and visit doctors more 
frequently a federal study says 
the national center for health statistics compared the health of 
nativeand foreignborn residents of the united states aged 18 and 
over and found that the newcomers appear to be the healthier group 
dr gerry e hendershot author of the report health of the 
foreignborn population united states 198586 said a number of 
possible reasons could account for this difference 
one factor that certainly is involved is the selectivity of 
immigration to this country he said in a telephone interview 
this week 
people with higher educations and professional skills have a 
better opportunity to migrate to this country so people coming 
here tend to be from groups that have good health he said 
in addition the immigration and naturalization service does 
some health screening hendershot said plus immigrants tend to 
be younger on average than the general population and younger 
people in general tend to be healther than older people 
finally he noted that the study was based on interviews with 
58682 households by looking at household groups the analysis 
would not include transients such as migrant workers who may tend 
to be in poorer health hendershot commented 
he added that he hoped to undertake another study in the future 
aimed at detailing the reasons for health differences 
according to the survey 
