<DOCNO> AP880629-0123 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today barred states from 
placing sweeping strict regulations on professional forprofit 
organizations that solicit contributions for charities 
the justices by a 72 vote ruled that a north carolina law 
that imposed such regulations violated freespeech rights 
numerous charitable groups such as the national federation of 
the blind the american red cross and the easter seal society had 
urged the court to disallow north carolinas regulations for 
fundraising they said the restrictions severely threatened 
charities ability to raise money 
the north carolina regulations would have forced fundraising 
organizations solicitors to tell prospective contributors what 
percentage of the money they raised over the past 12 months had 
been used for expenses and fundraising fees 
the forprofit solicitors also would have been required to 
disclose before requesting a contribution the approximate 
percentage of money that would go for charity 
the 1985 north carolina law also required forprofit fundraising 
organizations to be licensed and generally regarded fundraising 
costs greater than 35 percent of contributions to be unreasonable 
and illegal 
the law was aimed at preventing fraud and applied to telephone 
and doortodoor solicitations 
north carolina officials had discovered that some forprofit 
fundraisers kept between 75 percent and 85 percent of the money 
raised for various charities in no case did the officials find a 
professional fundraising organization pay more than half of its 
revenues to the charities in whose names the money was raised 
justice william j brennan writing for the court today said 
each of north carolinas requirements violates freespeech rights 
the interest in protecting charities and the public from fraud 
is of course a sufficiently substantial interest to justify a 
narrowly tailored regulation brennan said 
the question then is whether the north carolina law is 
sufficiently tailored to this remaining interest we conclude that 
it is not he said 
the decision likely will carry an immediate impact for dozens of 
local and state regulations seeking to ensure that the bulk of 
charitable contributions actually go to charities 
only a few other states maine tennessee and indiana among 
them have enacted laws requiring financial disclosures during 
solicitation and the laws in those states ran into adverse court 
rulings too 
todays decision calls those laws into question 
brennan was joined today by justices byron r white thurgood 
marshall harry a blackmun and anthony m kennedy justices 
antonin scalia and john paul stevens joined most of brennans 
opinion 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justice sandra day 
oconnor dissented 
the court in 1980 and again in 1984 barred states from limiting 
the amount of money charities that do their own fundraising spend 
on such campaigns 
in 1980 the justices struck down a schamburg ill ordinance 
that prohibited doortodoor solicitation of contributions by 
charitable organizations that could not prove they used at least 75 
percent of their revenues for charitable purposes 
in 1984 the justices voted 54 to overturn a maryland law that 
barred charities and charitable fundraisers from soliciting 
contributions if more than 25 percent of the revenue was consumed 
by fundraising costs 
the maryland law allowed charities to spend more than 25 percent 
of revenues on fundraising costs if they could show they were 
unable to raise money under the legal limitation 
the justices said in the maryland case that high solicitation 
costs were not an accurate measure of fraud 
today the court said north carolinas law does not differ 
significantly from the maryland law with which it found fault 
the case is riley vs national federation of the blind of north 
carolina 87328 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0124 </DOCNO>
