<TEXT>
the knoxville tenn newssentinel on lineitem vetoes 
if the president had a lineitem veto would it be easier for 
him to fight spending excesses on capitol hill though common sense 
says yes opponents of the idea cite discouraging evidence from 
states that already have this budget device they say that on the 
average these states have no more success in restraining outlays 
than other states 
but george mason university economist mark crain currently on 
leave to the white house budget office has conducted a more 
detailed analysis he reports that not all lineitem vetoes are 
created equal the most effective type seems to be the 
itemreduction veto which allows a governor to substitute a 
lower dollar figure than the one sought by the legislature for a 
particular item only 10 states have this budget device 
crain finds that when all other variables are held constant the 
itemreduction veto slashes average annual spending increases by 
more than half from 4 percent to 13 percent 
over the years that adds up to enormous savings crains 
findings make the case for a strong lineitem veto more convincing 
than ever 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 26 
the orange county calif register on tougher drug laws 
the law authorizing the seizure of vehicles involved in drug 
transactions was intended to punish smugglers and bigtime dealers 
by taking trucks or dopeladen tugboats at the same time the drugs 
themselves were confiscated now the authorities claim the 
right to confiscate a vehicle with a few marijuana seeds on or in 
it and sell it at auction unless the owner takes the initiative of 
contesting the seizure the owner doesnt need to be convicted of 
selling buying or possessing an illicit drug to lose the vehicle 
such a penalty for a minor crime for which punishment is already 
prescribed by law is intended to frighten smalltimers not bother 
big dealers 
the drug law catch22 is on display here the more drug laws 
drive up the price of illicit drugs the more tempting the trade 
will be and the more violent and utterly unscrupulous people will 
dominate it 
drug laws do not keep drugs away from those who want them and 
they have unfortunate sideeffects like massive increases in real 
crimes such as mugging and robbery the latest escalation simply 
illustrates the point it should be abandoned and we should move 
to something constructive like a spirited debate about drug 
legalization 
</TEXT>
