<TEXT>
the supreme court ruling for a michigan farm 
family accused of enslaving two retarded men for more than 10 
years said today that illegal involuntary servitude cannot be 
imposed through psychological coercion alone 
by a 90 vote the justices rejected reagan administration 
arguments that the legal definition of involuntary servitude should 
be broad enough to include psychological coercion 
if the court had agreed with federal prosecutors the broader 
definition of involuntary servitude outlawed by the 
constitutions 13th amendment which abolished slavery and by 
federal law could have jeopardized certain cult groups or 
religious orders that use psychological persuasion to enlist and 
retain members 
absent change by congress the term involuntary servitude 
necessarily means a condition of servitude in which the victim is 
forced to work for the defendant by the use or threat of physical 
restraint or physical injury or by the use of threat or coercion 
through law or the legal process justice sandra day oconnor 
wrote for the court 
ike and margarethe kozminski who own a dairy farm in chelsea 
mich were convicted of keeping robert fulmer and louis molitoris 
in involuntary servitude 
both men are mentally retarded fulmer has an iq of 67 and spent 
most of his life in foster homes in training school or working on 
farms molitoris who has an iq of 60 was unemployed and living on 
the streets of ann arbor when he met the kozminskis 
at trial federal prosecutors introduced evidence that the two 
men received no pay for their work were physically abused were 
given woefully inadequate housing and were told they could not 
leave the farm 
the kozminskis introduced evidence tending to controvert some of 
that evidence 
after a federal jury convicted them the kozminskis received 
suspended prison sentences and were placed on probation for two 
years ike kozminski also was fined 20000 and ordered to pay 
fulmer and molitoris over 6000 each in restitution 
the couples son john was convicted of a conspiracy charge he 
was given a suspended prison sentence placed on two years 
probation and fined 10000 
the 6th us circuit court of appeals threw out the convictions 
last year ruling that the presiding trial judge erred in telling 
jurors about involuntary servitude 
the judge said it may include situations in which coercive 
acts or words cause persons in employment to believe they cannot 
freely leave employment if the acts are done or the words are 
spoken with the intent to cause this result 
the 6th circuit court said the judges instructions could be 
interpreted to mean that purely psychological coercion could 
amount to involuntary servitude too broad a legal definition 
the appeals court said involuntary servitude must feature 
physical or legal coercion or fraud and deceit used against a 
victim who is a minor an immigrant or a mental incompetent 
the appeals court sent the kozminskis case back for a new trial 
so a jury could decide whether the retarded men were victimized by 
fraud and deceit in an effort to retain their services 
reagan administration lawyers while not challenging the need 
for a new trial argued that the 6th circuit courts ruling defined 
involuntary servitude too narrowly 
today the supreme court sent the kozminskis case back for a 
new trial stating the judges instructions may have caused the 
kozminskis to be convicted for conduct that does not violate 
federal law 
but oconnors opinion said the record in the farm familys case 
contains sufficient evidence of physical or legal coercion to 
enable a jury to convict the kozminskis even under the stricter 
standard of involuntary servitude that we announce today 
the case is us vs kozminski 862000 
</TEXT>
