<TEXT>
patrick sherrill who shot and killed 14 
fellow postal workers two years ago slipped through a lax 
screening system for new employees congressional investigators 
said wednesday 
and although the postal officials rushed help to the families of 
victims immediately after the aug 20 1986 edmond okla 
tragedy the agency then dropped the ball the general accounting 
office reported 
a study of 15 post offices released by rep glenn english 
dokla indicated that out of 1289 newly hired employees 816 
were hired without checking their job histories with former 
employers and police checks were not done for 748 gao reported 
assistant postmaster general john s trosch responded that 10 
states have established policies of not providing criminal history 
information for employment purposes and many employers are 
reluctant to release details about former workers out of fear they 
will be sued as the source of prejudicial information or for 
invasion of privacy but the agency is working to tighten its 
hiring and screening practices he said 
a separate gao report on the edmond slayings said that while 
the postal service provided noteworthy immediate assistance to the 
families of victims it then turned the matter over to the oklahoma 
city division which offered further help only in response to 
direct appeals from the survivors 
the families were not contacted to see if they needed help 
because it was believed that such contacts would infringe on the 
families privacy during a time of grief subsequent criticism of 
the handling of the tragedy can be traced to this decision the 
gao said 
the study recommended that the postal service initiate 
contingency planning including crisis management in order to be 
prepared to deal with the traumatic effects of any future disasters 
in a response attached to the study postmaster general anthony 
frank said he accepts the findings and recommendations and will 
include the principles of crisis management in contingency plans 
sherrill a letter carrier killed 14 workers and wounded six 
others before killing himself 
