<TEXT>
each morning israel zamora reports to 
the job exchange hoping a farmer needs him and his family to hoe 
weeds competing with the lucrative sugar beet crop 
migrant laborers are in demand in the red river valley between 
minnesota and north dakota even more so this year as farmers try 
to salvage a cash crop that could determine if they survive or fail 
its too hot theres not enough rain a lot of the fields are 
too dry so its dirty said zamora 40 of weslaco texas 
showing his calloused nickedup hands 
but were poor this is how we make our living we never know 
whats going to happen the next day 
zamora was given the name of a farmer and directions to his 
place then he headed off with his family in a tattered white ford 
van that survived the threeday journey from texas for the next 12 
hours they hoed weeds for 30 an acre 
hundreds more migrants than usual almost all of them from the 
parched lands of texas made the 1500mile trip in pickups and 
vans to find seasonal work in minnesota thanks to unusual weather 
they found more work than normal 
everybodys working and i have 50 farmers waiting for more 
