the worst drought in 50 years is only one problem facing the 
beets which ripen into tannishwhite bulbs that produce sugar a 
may 13 frost killed much of the first planting so farmers had to 
try again high winds hampered the second seeding and survivors 
are enduring the drought and an onslaught of weeds 
farmers spray chemicals to control weeds which suck up moisture 
from the ground and keep it from the beets but the herbicides 
dont work unless it rains if it rains now the weeds grow twice 
as fast as the beets 
if the chemicals dont kill the weeds the laborers will 
theyre like insurance to an automobile owner said pablo 
guajardo of the job service division in moorhead 
the red river flows north into canada through a lush 
200milelong valley that was once the bed of a glacial lake the 
heavy rich soil is among the most fertile in the world 
sugar beets are a 1 billion industry in the valley which 
produces about 20 percent of the sugar made in the united states 
about 12 percent of the us total comes from an 1800member 
cooperative called the american sugar crystal co which expects 
the yield to be down substantially this year because of the drought 
crop projections are 16 tons per acre on 366000 acres down 
from last years yield of 19 tons per acre according to ron hayes 
president of american crystal 
but the beets have fared better than wheat barley and other 
light grains on the parched prairie so growers are concentrating 
on them 
