farmers got 
about 4400 migrants are in moorhead including 1400 who are 
laborers they arrived in april and may but had no work early 
because of the weather 
however with the late start and and the drought theyll 
probably have work into august 
the migrants normally get paid 22 an acre or a minimum of 5 
an hour because of the increased demand some are getting 30 to 
35 an acre and a good hoer can work two acres per day seven days 
a week 
at the job exchange men with folded arms sat in chairs against 
a wall at a former high school looking like anxious students 
waiting to see the principal they waited for word on work and 
talked about the weather barefoot children scurried about or drew 
pictures on papers 
its a pretty bad year too many weeds said rodolfo 
gonzalez 46 wearing a los angeles dodgers baseball cap one 
good thing about the drought though no mosquitoes 
bennie hernandez had just driven 14 hours from wyoming because 
he heard there were jobs here after this job hell go to iowa to 
hack weeds with a machete in the soybean fields 
you dont know from one day to the next we just move and hope 
to find work hernandez said 
the work is exhausting workers chop at kneehigh weeds along 
straight rows of beets stopping occasionally for water the lunch 
break lasts 30 minutes 
the migrants took a chance on the droughtstricken north because 
job opportunities are scarcer in texas 
at least up here they have hope the economy in texas is not 
the best theres nothing down there to begin with said guajardo 
the migrants dont harvest the beets thats done by machine in 
october when the crop is cut into slices like french fries and 
mixed with water to remove the sugar 
farmers who have given up on their grain crops are keeping their 
fingers crossed on sugar beets 
gerald olsonawski of kittson county who plowed under 1400 
acres of failed wheat he has 321 acres of beets thats my last 
hope thats all i got to go on 
