approved by the house prevents federal money from being used for 
the planning design or construction of bypasses or access roads 
associated with the william center development just west of 
washington in prince william county va 
the development is being opposed by local groups who say it 
would be detrimental to the adjacent manassas national battlefield 
park 
this is designed to indicate congress interest in this piece 
of land said tad boggs an aide to rep robert mrazek dny 
who sponsored the provision this is a shot across the 
developers bow and is intended to buy us time until we come up 
with a plan to purchase the land 
the bill is the first piece of legislation passed by the house 
that attempts to stop the 542acre development which historians 
claim would violate the sanctity of the 4600acre park where two 
major civil war battles were fought 
the projects developers have offered to help pay for road 
construction but federal funds usually are needed for a project of 
this size to be completed mrazeks provision prohibits federal 
involvement in road bypasses or alterations associated with 
interstate 66 which runs adjacent to the park and us 29 and 
state route 234 which run through the battle site 
