<TEXT>
mothers have the greatest influence in getting 
children to wear auto safety belts while fathers often set a bad 
example according to a survey of the nations school children 
the survey released wednesday showed 79 percent of those 
interviewed believe seat belts save lives and more children wear 
seat belts than the parents who accompany them 
of the 1118 children interviewed by louis harris and associates 
for the american coalition of traffic safety 58 percent said they 
wear seat belts all or most of the time while 57 percent said 
their mothers regularly wear seat belts and only 38 percent said 
their fathers buckle up 
acts which has a 15 million annual budget was set up by the 
us auto industry in 1986 to support safety belt use 
among the youngsters surveyed 30 percent said they use seat 
belts all of the time 28 percent most of the time and 33 
percent sometimes with 9 percent saying they never wear them 
pollsters interviewed children in grades 57 across the country 
in late april and may pollsters who talked to children in their 
schools claimed a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percent 
i cant believe i got out of that car alive said 9yearold 
nicole rabello of whiting nj an accident victim who was one of 
37 children presented at a news conference announcing the survey 
results all the children were saved because of seat belts 
according to acts officials 
blownup photographs of smashed cars including the 
mercedesbenz in which nicole was riding provided a backdrop 
elevenyearold frederick d thompson of washington dc said 
that he has only forgotten to put on his seat belt once since his 
crash and his father quickly reminded him 
if i was not wearing my safety belt my head would have gone 
through the window of the car frederick said 
susan akin miss america for 1986 accompanied the children and 
recounted that a seat belt saved her life in a 1987 mississippi 
crash involving her car and an 18wheel truck 
one rainy day i was in a hospital with blood running down my 
face said miss akin she said family cried when they saw her 
covered with blood but thank goodness they were not tears 
looking down on me dead 
miss akin said since the crash which left only a small scar on 
her nose she has volunteered her time to promote the use of seat 
belts 
phil haseltine acts executive director said the survey showed 
that parents are a greater influence on safety belt use than 
entertainers sports figures or police officers involved in safety 
campaigns 
but fathers dont look too good here said haseltine 
the survey said 48 percent of those surveyed wished their 
parents would use seat belts more often while 68 percent worry 
about their parents being killed in an auto accident only 38 
percent said they worry about dying in a car crash themselves 
the survey said 83 percent of the children interviewed correctly 
identified whether their states are among the 32 with mandatory 
seat belt laws the district of columbia also has such a law 
the survey said safety belt use is signficantly higher among 
children in states with laws than in states without them 64 
percent versus 37 percent 
</TEXT>
