<TEXT>
a medicine widely used for gout appears to 
dramatically slow the lethal destruction of cirrhosis but doctors 
disagree over whether it should become routine treatment for this 
major killer 
in a report published thursday a team of mexican researchers 
said they found a striking consistent statistically significant 
benefit of the drug colchicine after 10 years more than half of 
those who got the medicine were alive compared with less than a 
quarter of the people in an untreated comparison group 
earlier versions of the 14year study have been published and 
presented at medical meetings over the years and many us experts 
are familiar with the work despite the impressive results 
however opinion is divided 
some believe colchicine should be used for cirrhosis despite 
flaws in the mexican research because the drug is clearly safe and 
inexpensive others contend that more research is necessary to 
prove that it works 
cirrhosis is scarring of the liver that usually results from 
alcohol abuse or chronic viral infections it is the ninth leading 
cause of death among us adults killing about 20000 people 
annually 
according to the world health organization it accounts for 13 
deaths for each 100000 people annually in the united states and 
as high as 32 in italy and 42 in hungary 
until now doctors treating cirrhosis have been able to do 
little except encourage patients to stop drinking 
we are the first ones to show that you can really do something 
for the cirrhosis patient said dr marcos rojkind who directed 
the latest study at the salvador zubiran national institute for 
nutrition in mexico city 
he concluded that colchicine stops the progression of cirrhosis 
and in some cases even seems to reverse the disease colchicine is 
widely used to treat gout a hereditary form of arthritis caused by 
excess uric acid in the blood and it attacks joints in the hands 
and feet 
rojkind who is now at albert einstein college of medicine in 
new york said he believes colchicine works by reducing 
inflammation in the liver and preventing the release of a growth 
factor that promotes the formation of connective tissue 
in an editorial published with the study in the new england 
journal of medicine drs james l boyer and david f ransohoff of 
yale medical school pointed out shortcomings in the study among 
other things they noted that those who received the drug were not 
as sick as those in the comparison group 
these questions about chance bias and biologic factors tend 
to weaken an endorsement of what is otherwise the most impressive 
outcome yet described for any treatment of patients with 
cirrhosis they wrote 
they said more research is needed dr jay hoffnagle of the 
national institute of diabetes digestive and kidney diseases 
agreed 
its the type of work that needs to be repeated to show that 
its a reproducible finding he said 
hoffnagle said the drug should not be routinely used for 
cirrhosis and he said he believes that many us experts are 
skeptical of the findings 
however dr thomas lamont of boston university medical center 
said he thinks colchicine should be offered now to victims of the 
disease 
while its a flawed study he said we have no other 
simple medical therapy for this disease coupled with abstinence 
from alcohol which we firmly believe in this therapy is certainly 
worth further consideration 
dr marhsall kaplan of new england medical center has 
successfully used the drug to treat a rare form of the disease 
called primary biliary cirrhosis and he agreed that colchicine 
should be used for cirrhosis resulting from alcoholism and other 
causes 
if a drug seems to have a benefit and doesnt have any risk 
and is inexpensive and with colchicine all of these things are 
true its probably reasonable to try it he said 
in the study 54 patients were randomly assigned to take 
colchicine while 46 got placebo pills after five years 75 
percent of the colchicine patients were alive compared with 34 
percent of the placebo group after 10 years the survival rate in 
the two groups was 56 percent and 20 percent 
biopsies seemed to show improvement in nine of those who got 
colchicine in two of them their livers had returned to normal 
while in seven others there was minimal scarring 
the two major side effects of the treatment were diarrhea and 
gastritis or inflammation of the stomach 
</TEXT>
