a grandfather clock that belonged to 
a man believed to have helped organize the boston tea party 215 
years ago has been sold for 440000 
the silverdial clock was originally owned by nathaniel bradlee 
believed to be one of the 58 organizers of the dec 16 1773 tax 
revolt he had kept at what is now tremont street in boston where 
the tea party was planned 
the clock was sold by kennebunkport auctioneer richard w oliver 
its called the boston tea party clock oliver said how 
much more historical can you get 
the successful bidder emile dumont of hampton falls nh 
plans to build a wing in his heritage inn in chelmsford mass for 
the clock oliver said 
the clock had belonged to a 78yearold retired stockbroker from 
wiscasset who said he decided to sell it at saturdays auction 
because he had difficulty insuring it 
brewster d doggett inherited the clock from his father in 1939 
