<TEXT>
the canadian embassy doesnt have to look far for 
advice on how to cope with the loss of most of its soviet employees 
in a titfortat spy war they can ask the americans across town 
on wednesday kremlin officials handed the canadians a list of 
25 soviet employees no longer be allowed to work at the embassy 
said the missions spokesman paul drager the soviets had actually 
stopped working monday 
american diplomats stationed a few blocks away in downtown 
moscow know the feeling they lost all 260 of their soviet support 
staff in october 1986 
the latest pullout comes at a particularly hard time for the 
canadians while they are trying to follow developments in the 
first soviet communist party conference in 47 years and just 
before fridays celebration of the canada day holiday 
by tradition canadas ambassador is given time on soviet 
television to address the soviet people on the holiday it is not 
clear whether the spy dispute will affect this tradition 
the problems began june 22 when canada announced it was 
expelling eight soviet diplomats and officials for alleged 
espionage nine other soviets previously assigned to canada were 
barred from returning the soviets retaliated the next day 
expelling two canadian diplomats and saying three others cannot 
come back 
canada shot back by kicking out the senior military attache at 
the soviet embassy in ottawa and barring a former second secretary 
from returning on saturday the soviets ordered canadas military 
attache to leave moscow told seven former diplomats they cannot 
return and pulled out the 25 soviet workers 
the withdrawal leaves the canadian embassy with just 14 soviet 
employees the hardesthit section is the one that issues visas for 
soviets traveling to canada drager said two of the three soviets 
who worked in the visa section have left meaning soviets citizens 
will have to wait longer to get permission to visit canada drager 
said the blow comes at a time when soviets travel to canada is 
soaring because of new more liberal soviet regulations he said 
the withdrawn employees include carpenters painters drivers 
mechanics translators and maintenance workers the canadian 
embassy is trying to replace those workers with spouses and 
children of diplomats and of other canadians living in moscow such 
as businessmen and journalists 
the problem is a familiar one for the us embassy after the 
soviet union withdrew its employees us diplomats had to take 
over much of the cooking cleaning driving and telephone 
answering they also lost valuable soviet translators eventually 
an american company was hired to send in support staff 
like the americans the canadians who number 42 are adopting a 
positive attitude 
we can function and we will function drager quoted canadian 
ambassador vernon turner as saying 
drager however said a longterm solution to the staff shortage 
has yet to be found its much too early to say he said 
the canadians are hoping the kremlin will allow some of the 
withdrawn soviets to return or be replaced on monday canadian 
foreign minister joe clark told reporters in ottawa after meeting 
with soviet ambassador alexei rodionov that soviet workers coming 
to montreal to rebuild the firedamaged soviet consulate may not 
get visas unless the kremlin reverses its withdrawal of the 25 
soviets 
managers of canadian embassy programs have given turner lists of 
jobs to be done according to priority drager said asked if job 
assignments of diplomats had been changed because of the staff 
shortage he responded were doing a lot of different things 
were certainly coping 
drager refused to say if the diplomats were working longer hours 
and declined to say whether the canadian embassy had asked the 
americans for advice on how to cope us embassy marguerite squire 
also declined comment 
