the transportation department broadened its 
proposed drug testing requirements wednesday to include more than 
350000 workers in the mass transit merchant marine and pipeline 
industries 
the action follows earlier announcements of proposed regulations 
that would require a variety of drug tests for workers in 
safetyrelated jobs in aviation interstate bus and trucking and 
the railroads 
none of the regulations has been put into effect and some 
already are under court challenge 
transportation secretary jim burnley said the testing 
requirements for mass transit workers merchant seamen and 
employees of companies that transport natural gas or hazardous 
liquids through pipelines comports with his goal of discouraging 
drug abuse in all sectors 
it is crucial that we send a zero tolerance message to all 
segments of our population regarding drug abuse the 
transportation industry included burnley said in a statement 
the new proposed regulation as the previous ones involving 
aviation trucking and the railroads calls for a variety of drug 
tests including random tests for employees involved in 
safetyrelated jobs 
the transportation department estimates about 108000 workers 
including vehicle operators and maintenance workers would be 
subject to the requirements covering mass transit systems such as 
city bus and subway lines 
another 132000 seamen on commercial vessels and an estimated 
116500 employees of companies that operate pipeline facilities for 
natural gas and hazardous liquids would be covered by the 
regulation the department said 
under the proposed rule the us coast guard would require the 
owners of commercial ships to conduct the testing program if the 
tests are not required the coast guard could lift the marine 
operators license the department said 
pipeline operators who also could lose their license also 
would be responsible for testing their employees under the 
regulation 
local transit officials could lose federal transit subsidies 
under the regulation unless they conduct the required testing 
programs 
