<TEXT>
the supreme court decision upholding the 
validity of independent counsels clears the way for the sentencing 
of former white house aide michael k deaver for lying under oath 
about his lobbying business 
the trial judge in deavers case had stayed further proceedings 
in the case after a federal appellate court in washington struck 
down the constitutionality of the independent counsel law last 
january 
but the supreme courts decision wednesday removes an important 
element of deavers challenge to his prosecution though his 
lawyers say they have other issues to raise when they appeal the 
conviction 
the decision also means that former white house political 
director lyn nofziger will have to rely on other issues to appeal 
his conviction and 90day sentence for illegally lobbying former 
reagan administration colleagues 
and the decision dispels any doubt about the legal authority of 
independent counsel lawrence e walsh to prosecute former white 
house aide oliver l north and other defendants on charges stemming 
from the irancontra arms and money affair 
the independent counsel statute provides a workable solution 
to a difficult problem walsh who had accepted a backup 
appointment said in a statement we are gratified that the 
supreme court has upheld the constitutionality of that statute 
the prosecutor in deavers case independent counsel whitney 
north seymour said in a brief statement wednesday that he would 
ask us district judge thomas penfield jackson to reschedule the 
sentencing at an early date so the deaver case can then move on 
through the appeal to its final conclusion 
seymour who declined to accept a parallel appointment from the 
justice department to blunt the effect of contitutional challenges 
to the statute called the high courts decision a major victory 
for the public interest 
deaver could receive a fiveyear sentence for each of three 
felony convictions of lying to a grand jury and the house energy 
and commerce investigations subcommittee about the lobbying 
business he formed after leaving president reagans staff in 1985 
deaver was found guilty of lying when he denied or said he 
couldnt recall lobbying former administration colleagues on behalf 
of private clients 
