<TEXT>
prime minister noboru takeshita has decided to push 
for tax reform putting his 8monthold job on the line on an issue 
that his two predecessors were unable to tackle 
the plan already has drawn substantial opposition in an unusual 
display of protest some japanese motorists have pasted bumper 
stickers on their cars that say we oppose the valueadded tax 
an editorial in the nationwide newspaper asahi shimbun urged 
takeshita to submit the plan to a national referendum and should 
such efforts fail then the obvious step would be to dissolve the 
lower house and call a general election 
previous attempts at tax reform have met with little success 
the late prime minister masayoshi ohira unsuccessfully tried to 
introduce a general excise tax in 1979 and failed 
takeshitas predecessor yasuhiro nakasone tried to push a 5 
percent sales tax through the legislature last year and suffered an 
embarrassing setback when he had to withdraw it 
later in local elections nakasones governing liberal 
democratic party suffered severe losses over the sales tax issue 
the general feeling is that takeshitas political career is 
riding on the outcome of his tax plan 
prime minister takeshita said that he will put his 
political life on this said a foreign ministry spokesman who 
demanded anonymity this could be rather dangerous 
the diet or japanese parliament has agreed to return from its 
summer recess to take up the issue in an extraordinary 120day 
session beginning july 11 
in a statement to the nation takeshita said tuesday that the 
current tax system relies too heavily on direct taxes especially 
taxes derived from salary increases as a result as you already 
know there has been a growing sentiment among salaried workers 
that the tax system is too heavy and unfair 
some japanese oppose the current system because it relies almost 
entirely on direct taxes and provides substantial tax breaks for 
certain groups such as politicians and doctors 
as japanese incomes have risen so has their tax burden to the 
point where many japanese have resorted to tax evasion 
the national tax agency reported on june 23 that tax evasion had 
reached a record high the agency said it uncovered unreported 
revenues totaling 518 million in fiscal 1987 up 29 million over 
the previous record set in 1985 
however critics say takeshitas plan is flawed and leaves too 
many loopholes without providing enough relief to middleincome 
families 
