<TEXT>
the supreme court in a decision that may 
signal an end to capital punishment for young killers overturned 
an oklahoma mans death sentence wednesday 
four of the eight justices who voted in the case said the death 
penalty for convicted murderers who committed their crimes before 
reaching age 16 always amounts to unlawfully cruel and unusual 
punishment 
three justices said the constitution imposes no such age 
limitation on imposing capital punishment 
in her controlling vote justice sandra day oconnor voiced 
serious doubts whether states may execute people for crimes 
committed when only 15 
although i believe that a national consensus forbidding the 
execution of any person for a crime committed before the age of 16 
very likely does exist i am reluctant to adopt this conclusion as 
a matter of constitutional law without better evidence than we now 
possess oconnor said 
but she supplied a fifth vote to overturn oklahoma death row 
inmates william wayne thompsons death sentence ruling that the 
states death penalty law could not be applied to him because the 
law has no minimum age 
there is a considerable risk that the oklahoma legislature 
either did not realize that its actions would have the effect of 
rendering 15yearold defendants deatheligible or did not give the 
question serious consideration oconnor said 
she added that thompson and others who committed their crimes 
before age 16 may not be executed under the authority of a 
capital punishment statute that specifies no minimum age at which 
the commission of a capital crime can lead to the offenders 
execution 
but wednesdays ruling left unclear whether oconnor would vote 
to strike down a death penalty law that explicitly made 15yearold 
murderers eligible for execution 
the decision also left unclear whether the court would find 
fault with death penalty laws in which convicted killers who were 
16 or 17 when they committed their crimes are eligible for 
execution 
as a practical matter 15 year olds wil not be executed in 
this country predicted paul l hoffman a los angeles lawyer who 
represented amnesty international in urging the justices to abolish 
capital punishment for juveniles 
justice oconnor walked right up to the edge of saying that 
hoffman said 
in oklahoma assistant attorney general david lee said the 
line has been drawn in my opinion our reading of the opinion is 
that the court used 16 as the line 
if hoffman and lee are correct the decision will affect only 
about 30 of the some 2100 death row inmates nationwide 
of the 100 men and women executed in us prisons since the 
supreme court in 1976 allowed states to resume capital punishment 
three died for murders committed when they were 17 
charles rumbaugh was executed in texas in 1985 james terry 
roach in south carolina in 1986 and jay pinkerton in texas in 1986 
since 1948 no one has been executed in this country for a crime 
committed when he or she was younger than 17 
of the 37 states with death penalty laws 19 of them do not 
specify a minimum age of the 18 state laws that do impose a 
minimum age none of them allows execution of killers younger than 
16 when they committed their crimes 
thirteen states and the district of columbia do not allow 
capital punishment 
justices john paul stevens william j brennan thurgood 
marshall and harry a blackmun voted to ban the death penalty for 
any crime committed by someone not yet 16 
writing for the four stevens said imposing death to such 
criminals is nothing more than the purposeless and needless 
imposition of pain and suffering and thus an unconstitutional 
punishment 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justices antonin scalia 
and byron r white voted to let thompson die writing for the 
three scalia said he found thompsons age inadequate grounds for 
reversal of his sentence 
justice anthony m kennedy who joined the court after 
thompsons case was argued did not participate in the case 
thompson now 20 was one of four people convicted in the jan 
29 1983 death in grady county okla of charles keene his 
former brotherinlaw 
all four including thompsons older brother were sentenced to 
death thompson was the only juvenile 
police said keene was beaten stabbed shot and thrown into a 
river 
