a test case has shown that a government 
takeover can restore some democracy to a corrupt teamsters local 
but the battle is far from over the locals courtappointed 
trustee said wednesday 
and labor observers stressed that the experience of teamsters 
local 560 in union city does not mean the justice department will 
be able to meet the far more ambitious goal it announced tuesday 
wresting control from the unions international leaders 
the success of a government takeover could depend on how much 
power a judge grants to a trustee said herman benson director of 
the brooklyn nybased association for union democracy a 
nonpartisan union rights group 
to eliminate union corruption you have to have massive 
government interaction said benson 
us attorney rudolph giuliani in new york filed suit tuesday 
describing the teamsters as dominated by the mafia seeking to have 
a federal judge remove from office any union officials who violated 
racketeering laws and appoint a trustee to supervise free elections 
in 1984 us district judge harold a ackerman ruled that a 
takeover of local 560 was necessary because of a quartercentury of 
brutal organized crime domination at the hands of the provenzano 
family ackerman appointed a trustee to clean up the local and 
bring on free elections 
it was the first time a union had been placed under government 
control 
benson points to recent improvements in allowing the 8500 
members of local 560 a voice in their union he said the changes 
have come under stewardship of edwin steir a former federal 
prosecutor on the job about a year 
i see enormous change since ive gotten here said steir 
citing discussion of past corruption among the rank and file 
people say things theyve never said before he said 
however theres still fear here and theres a lot of 
uncertainty about how to assert dissenting views he said 
attorney harvey weissbard who represents local 560s last 
president michael sciarra said giulianis office is going to face 
some highpowered legal talent and the prospect of lengthy 
appeals which could also bog down the process 
sciarra dismissed tuesdays lawsuit as a politically motivated 
unionbusting move that signaled a dark day for labor sciarra 
has the support of a large and vocal group of local 560 members 
about 2000 people appeared at a recent rally for him 
two candidates have emerged to oppose sciarra who rose to power 
under the deposed leadership 
weissbard said he plans to file a motion later this week to 
overturn ackermans 1984 decision based on a recent supreme court 
ruling a group of 260 truckers who joined the union after 1984 
have also sued to end the trusteeship 
the trustee took over local 560 in 1986 after an appeals courts 
upheld ackerman but only in recent months have forces organized to 
oppose the former allies of jailed expresident anthony tony 
pro provenzano who authorities say is a captain in the genovese 
crime family 
he has been linked to the unsolved disappearance of national 
teamsters leader jimmy hoffa in 1975 
steir says he has had trouble building democracy because of a 
tradition of suppression of dissent that made fear and cynicism his 
main enemies 
benson said the very size of the international union could be an 
asset in allowing more open discussion among the rank and file 
the international at least is not one monolithic block of 
crooks he said 
on the other hand said labor law expert michael goldberg a 
university of pittsburgh law school associate professor a trustee 
of the international will have to contend with thousands of local 
leaders who may not cooperate 
new york university law professor james jacobs pointed out that 
the function of a local and the international are different and it 
is difficult to draw conclusions from local 560s experience 
there youre really running a union at the grass roots he 
said in the internationals case youre talking about an 
overarching management of the whole administration 
whether local 560 has been freed from the taint of organized 
crime is still an open question 
