<TEXT>
a concern about spreading aids through donated 
blood along with an improvement in surgical techniques has led a 
national institutes of health panel to recommend to doctors that 
blood transfusions be kept to a minimum and that traditional 
uses of blood be reevaluated 
the chances of contracting acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
from donated blood is still considered miniscule said tibor 
greenwalt a university of cincinnati researcher and chairman of 
the nih committee but he warned wednesday that blood transfusions 
do carry documented risks of infection and immune changes 
he and other committee members issued a report that recommended 
doctors reevaluate their use of blood transfusions during surgery 
and use their clinical judgment instead of a traditional 
formula to decide when transfusions are needed 
blood transfusions were once believed to be relatively safe 
but more recently many physicians and patients have come to regard 
them as potentially dangerous the report said 
the fear of aids has already caused a decreased usage of 
blood greenwalt told reporters in my community it is down by 
7 percent 
but he said the transfusion of donated blood the socalled 
homologous transfusion remains a therapeutic mainstay that 
continues to save thousands of lives particularly during the 
emergency treatment of wounds and other injuries 
despite a call for caution the committee report said that the 
chances contracting aids is only a remote hazard because of donor 
selection and laboratory screening procedures it is variously 
estimated that the risk of aids transmission by transfusion 
is 1 to 40000 to 1 to 1 million 
but the report warned that level of risk is unlikely to be 
appreciably decreased in the foreseeable future even if additional 
screening tests are added 
patients receiving blood transfusions are more likely to 
contract hepatitis with the risks rated as low as 1 in 100 for 
some types of this viral disease the committee report said 
greenwalt said the risks of disease increase with each 
additional unit of donated blood used by a patient and as a 
result the use of such blood should be kept to a minimum 
the committee said doctors should reexamine a basic surgical 
tenent called the 1030 rule that has been in use for decades 
the rule applies to the findings of blood tests given routinely 
to patients before surgery the first number refers to the numbers 
of hemoglobin or red oxygencarrying cells in the blood the 
second number is the hematocrit a measure of the percentage of 
cells in the blood low counts such as 1030 indicate anemia and 
lead surgeons to give transfusions routinely before surgery 
but the committee said the available evidence does not support 
the necessity for the 1030 rule it recommended that doctors 
instead make specific clinical evaluations of each patient and to 
use as little transfusion blood as is appropriate 
improved surgical procedures along with a better understanding 
of anemia the report said shows that patients with lower 
readings if otherwise healthy can do well in surgery without 
transfusions 
greenwalt said the committee also recommended that where 
possible patients should be given their own blood during surgery 
this can be done in two ways prior to surgery patients can 
give blood that is stored and then reinfused when needed or blood 
from a sterile surgical wound can be collected processed and 
returned to the patient using equipment now on the market 
your own blood is always the safest to get greenwalt 
said 
</TEXT>
