just under an inch of rain fell on the hughes farm overnight 
and that comes on top of a 25 inch downpour earlier in the month 
what this does is its kind of a tantalizing rain hughes 
said it prolongs things and it makes my corn look better 
simon warned reporters not to jump to any quick conclusions 
about the status of the crop simply because it looked good 
dont get any false impressions even though that corn looks 
better simon said 
vice president george bush the certain republican nominee had 
a similar farm visit in wisconsin on wednesday 
hughes said his farm presents a fairly lush backdrop for a 
drought tour really im a little embarrassed by it he said 
but he said even crops which look good now will soon be 
threatened by dry weather 
this is a point that were going to have to drive home real 
hard with people who arent familiar with farming hughes said 
my corn is six or seven feet high and getting ready to tassel 
but if we have some more searing heat and no rain i dont have 
stalks with enough vigor to produce ears 
hughes said recent rainfalls are far too little and too 
scattered to do much about ending this years drought 
it gives me a few more days over the farmer who didnt get 
any he said 
to illustrate how fickle these rains are i have a dear friend 
just north of here who only got twohundredths while indianola just 
south of here got an inch its just in a little pocket hughes 
said 
