<TEXT>
a tiny computer chip that can be glued to 
the bodies of killer bees to track their movements may help 
control migration of the pests into the united states according to 
the defense contractor designing the device 
engineers for martin marietta known for its production of mx 
missiles and laserguided artillery shells developed the 
sophisticated tracking chip at the oak ridge national laboratory in 
oak ridge tenn the company said tuesday 
the microchip about the size of a halfcarat diamond and 
weighing about as much as a grain of salt is part of an integrated 
circuit that would be attached to the midsections of captured bees 
the device is powered by nine solar cells and will transmit an 
infrared signal that can be picked up by a ground station up to a 
mile away 
a captured bee would have the device to be glued to its body and 
then be set free a spokesman said the transmitters may have to be 
attached to hundereds or thousands of bees 
what weve done so faris establish that the bee could 
indeed fly with the chip attached said ed aebischer a spokesman 
at the laboratory the entomologists have looked at it and 
theyre convinced that its workable 
a working killer bee transmitter is expected to be put in the 
field by next year 
martin marietta engineers plan to use the device to monitor the 
mating and foraging habits of the creatures known as killer bees 
because of their aggressiveness 
the bees are descendants of african queen bees hundreds of 
thousands of the bees have been heading north from brazil since 
they accidentally escaped from a laboratory in 1957 
they have killed 350 people since 1957 said ralph bram an 
official with the us agricultural research service the killer 
bees have migrated as far as southern mexico and bram estimates 
they could cross into texas as early as next year 
scientists hope that by being able to track the insects they can 
control the migration without using large quantities of pesticides 
the bees pose a threat to the 20 billion annual production of 
us agricultural crops requiring bee pollination said diedre 
falter one of the chips developers the microchip should be 
able to help combat this potentially very serious situation 
martin marietta operates the oak ridge laboratory under a 
government contract last year the company developed a handheld 
electronic detector that allowed scientists and beekeepers to 
distinguish between africanized bees and the domestic species by 
the different sounds they make 
