<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency on 
wednesday formally unveiled massive new draft regulations aimed at 
upgrading protection of 25 million farm workers from pesticides 
the agency said it was unable to estimate how many worker 
poisonings would be avoided as a result because no one knows how 
many are occuring now 
farmers using hired labor chemical manufacturers and others 
will have to spend an estimated 170 million to comply in the first 
year the regulations are effective and smaller sums after that 
said louis true head of program management and support in epas 
pesticide program 
the agency believes that a reduction in poisonings by onehalf 
to 1 percent would make the cost worthwhile he said without 
giving the basis for the calculation and insisting the agency does 
not know how frequent such poisonings are 
the regulations would extend protection to 300000 workers in 
greenhouses nurseries and forests who are not covered by existing 
rules they would not apply to noncommercial use in forests as by 
a park agency or to home use research use on rights of way or 
where the chemical is injected directly into the plant 
the agency circulated a draft of the new rules late last year to 
interest groups and congressional staffs in response early this 
year farm groups and labor organizations attacked various 
provisions but the draft released wednesday made no major changes 
the regulations will be open for comment for 90 days after 
publication next week and should be adopted sometime next year 
true said the 55 pages of two new regulations would replace a 
onepage regulation adopted in 1974 
major provisions include a requirement that fields be closed for 
24 hours or 48 hours after treatment with the most toxic carbamate 
and organophosphate compounds 
a host of other new provisions would be added ranging from the 
requirement for blood tests of employees of commercial applicators 
to the provision of water for washing off spills in the field and 
posting addresses and telephone numbers of the nearest emergency 
treatment facilities 
other important provisions try to fix responsibility more 
precisely for mishaps generally placing it on the farm owner or 
lessee and spelling out when hired applicators or others may be 
blamed 
true said it was implicit in the regulation that owners or 
lessees must make sure that contractors are aware of the new 
provisions perhaps well make that explicit after the 
comments he said 
true said the agency believes there are thousands of pesticide 
poisoning incidents every year but doubts estimates of hundreds of 
thousands a contractor once came up with an estimate of 12000 
which could not be supported he said 
the regulations do not apply where epa already has established 
rules for specific chemicals they are meant to add general 
protection while the agency is carrying out its laborious review of 
the 650 active ingredients in pesticides something it expects to 
finish only in the next century 
mark maslyn pesticide specialist for the american farm bureau 
federation said farmers would accept the new requirements in some 
instances but would oppose them in others i dont think theres 
any question people are willing to provide protective equipment to 
their mixers and loaders he said 
but as for the rules barring workers from reentering fields for 
certain periods after applications i think theres going to be 
an enforcement problem maslyn said in some particular cases 
its too long for farmers under pressure to get a crop to market 
he added 
shelly davis an attorney with the migrant legal action program 
said the proposed reentry intervals are not long enough and should 
be based on more than just acute toxicity she said i would 
establish a long interval for anything thats an actual or 
suspected carcinogen cause of cancer in animals like a week 
rep george brown dcalif complained that the new standards 
still arent stiff enough more stringent standards have been 
proven and accepted in california and texas without harm to the 
agricultural economy he wrote the epa 
