<TEXT>
the supreme court issuing a key civil rights 
ruling on the last day of its 198788 term made it easier 
wednesday for workers to prove their bosses are guilty of illegal 
discrimination 
the court by an 80 vote said employees can use statistical 
evidence to prove that some subjective decisions made by theilate federal 
law 
the decision means clara watson a former bank employee in fort 
worth texas gets a new day in court in her effort to prove she 
was discriminated against because she r 
employers viois black 
although involving a complicated aspect of federal antibias 
law wednesdays decision carries a significant direct impact on 
numerous lawsuits filed by women and members of racial minorities 
who say they have been treated unfairly 
it will have very broad ramifications said julius l 
chambers of the naacp legal defense fund that the court approved 
of statistical evidence in such cases is a major step 
but chambers and other civil rights lawyers voiced concern over 
language used by four justices in discussing how difficult it 
should be to prove with statistics that subjective decisions are 
illegally discriminatory 
its not clear how lower courts will implement that part of 
o a drivein 
teller and in 1980 was promoted to be a commercial teller in the 
banks main lobby 
over the course of the next year however ms watson applied 
unsuccessfully four times for promotions to supervisory positions 
in the bank 
she sued in 1981 charging racial bias in part her lawsuit 
contended that the bank discriminated against all blacks when it 
came to filling supervisory jobs 
ms watson offered statistics claiming that the same white 
supervisors who hired only 35 percent of black applicants hired 
148 percent of white applicants her lawsuit said the same 
supervisors rated blacks an average of 10 points lower than whites 
on annual salary evaluations and also promoted blacks from one 
salary level to another slower than they promoted whites 
her suit was dismissed by a federal trial judge and the 
dismissal was upheld by the new orleansbased 5th circuit court 
the appeals court rejected ms watsons contention that she had 
proved statistically that the bank discriminated against blacks 
the banks lawyers argued successfully before the 5th circuit 
court that statistics are irrelevant when evaluating subjective 
employment decisions 
but most other federal appeals courts had ruled that the 
disparate impact approach allowing the use of statistics may be 
used in challenging subjective employment decisions 
the reagan administration urged the justices to uphold the 5th 
circuit courts ruling saying employers otherwise might resort to 
fixed quotas in their selection practices 
in the courts main opinion wednesday justice sandra day 
oconnor said allowing the use of statistics in attacking objective 
employment policies would be rendered ineffective if statistics 
could not be used to challenge subjective management decisions as 
well 
we are persuaded that our decisions in 1971 and succeeding 
cases could largely be nullified if disparate impact analysis were 
applied only to standardized selection practices oconnor said 
so long as an employer refrained from making standardized 
criteria absolutely determinative it would remain free to give 
such tests almost as much weight as it chose without risking a 
disparate impact challenge 
that portion of her opinion attracted eight votes justice 
anthony m kennedy did not participate in the case 
but oconnor was speaking for only herself and three other 
justices when she said that offering statistical proof that an 
employers subjective management decisions are illegal will be 
tougher than attacking objective policies 
</TEXT>
