<TEXT>
a federal judge has ruled that ice cream 
maker haagendazs did not violate antitrust laws by withdrawing 
from a distribution arrangement that sold competing brands 
the state and federal laws may not be used as an ally in the 
dispute between haagendazs and two california companies us 
district judge charles a legge ruled tuesday 
the case which made headlines nationwide in 1985 involved two 
count a northern californiabased ice cream distributor and 
double rainbow a san francisco ice cream maker haagendazs was 
sued 
the decision said the haagendazs policy which has national 
implications neither violated antitrust laws nor the contractual 
rights of the distributor or manufacturer 
our company is delighted with this ruling said mark l 
stevens at haagendazs headquarters in teaneck nj our 
distributor policy is healthy for competition protecting our 
product at every step until it reaches our consumers hands is 
essential 
judge legge ruled haagendazs terminated two count because 
haagendazs has a marketing policy of requiring exclusive 
distribution which two count violated by agreeing to distribute 
ice creams of double rainbow as well as other brands that compete 
with haagendazs 
competition in the ice cream market is flourishing and 
interbrand competition is intense antitrust laws are no substitute 
for such true competition separate distribution has led to 
increased and successful interbrand competition 
</TEXT>
