<TEXT>
the us dollar edged higher early thursday against 
the japanese yen although it declined from its opening highs 
while stock prices rose in active trading in tokyo 
the dollar opened at 13290 yen up from wednesdays close of 
13240 yen but retreated to the 1324513255 yen level by 
midmorning 
the dollar fell because market participants were closing their 
positions prior to the long fourth of july holiday weekend in the 
united states said a dealer with a major securities firm speaking 
on condition of anonymity 
financial markets will be closed monday in the united states 
those who were buying the currency at the 133yen level at the 
start of trading moved down to 132 yen because of the upcoming 
holiday he said 
the dealer also attributed the dollars decline to bullish 
movement overnight in new york where the dollar briefly shattered 
the 134yen level 
the market today thursday is taking a break the dealer 
said 
but he added that he expected the dollar to bounce back against 
the yen as soon as the us holiday weekend was over so long as 
the bank of japan does not intervene in the market 
lack of intervention by japans central bank since last week has 
fueled the dollars surge on the tokyo foreign exchange market 
during a regular press conference earlier this week finance 
minister kiichi miyazawa ruled out the possibility of intervention 
and dismissed the current market gyrations as ordinary fluctuations 
however bank of japan governor satoshi sumita told a news 
conference wednesday the nations central bank was ready to take 
appropriate action to brake the dollars rise depending on how 
the us currency moves in the future 
the dollar has risen 345 yen in the past two trading days in 
tokyo 
on the tokyo stock exchange the nikkei stock average of 225 
selected issues up 20924 points on wednesday rose another 12303 
points to 2773036 by the end of the morning trading session 
the main market barometers climb was led mainly by heavy 
electricals shipping issues and shipbuilders traders said 
automakers also managed to move higher during the morning dealings 
</TEXT>
