<TEXT>
japan air lines has decided to purchase an 
additional 15 boeing jumbo jets for a total of 2 billion a jal 
spokesman said thursday 
spokesman kazuto yamamoto said the new b747400 aircraft with a 
twoperson cockpit seating capacity will be flown on international 
routes the first three aircraft would be delivered from the 
seattlebased us aircraft maker in 1990 
the decision reached during a jal board of directors meeting 
wednesday was made to win fierce competition in the introduction 
of the new type of aircraftand to meet our companys plan to 
increase its international flights yamamoto said 
with wednesdays decision jal will own 20 b747400 jumbo jets 
by the early 1990s four more than have been ordered by british 
airways and air france yamamato said 
jal placed an order to buy five boeing aircraft last september 
with the first to be delivered in august next year he said 
an official of a jal union representing 1360 crew members 
said labor unions oppose the planned introduction of the twoman 
cockpit aircraft for safety reasons 
the crew members union and another union representing 1890 
flight attendents went on a 48hour strike last tuesday and 
wednesday following disagreement with management over the number of 
cockpit crew members in the new aircraft 
we believe the new computer aboard the plane will not replace 
the flight engineer said the labor union official who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
she said the crew members union would meet thursday to decide 
what action to take against the managements plan to introduce the 
new aircraft 
during a shareholders meeting wednesday jals new chairman 
fumio watanabe was officially installed replacing susumu yamaji 
yamamoto quoted watanabe as saying at a news conference that he 
believed the cockpit crew issue will be solved through an 
exchange of opinions 
</TEXT>
